TY  - JOUR
AU  - Fich, Eliezer M
AU  - Xu, Guosong
T1  - Do salient climatic risks affect shareholder voting?
PY  - 2025
Y1  - 2025/03/01
DO  - 10.1093/rof/rfaf003
JO  - Review of Finance
JA  - Rev Financ
VL  - 29
IS  - 2
SP  - 567
EP  - 602
SN  - 1572-3097
AB  - Institutional investors affected by hurricanes subsequently support environmental proposals in non-affected firms even if they never voted for similar initiatives. Affected investors raise their holdings in firms where their pro-environment votes are consequential. The increased voting support after hurricanes has real effects as environmental proposals endorsed by more hurricane-afflicted investors are more likely to pass. Moreover, both market capitalization and analysts’ recommendations decline after firms pass environmental proposals. Our evidence suggests that natural disasters raise institutional investors’ concerns about the environment and about potential fund flow disruptions. These concerns, in turn, influence environmental activism, corporate policies, and firm performance.
Y2  - 4/24/2026
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rof/rfaf003
ER  - 




